I had the opportunity to the welcome Brett Gelman from Stranger Things along with singer & actress Ari Dayan to the Hostage Forum. They came with 2 simple agendas, to listen and help. 
I was so impressed with the patience and empathy they both displayed throughout their visit.
They met with family members of hostages and listened to their stories, not just to check a box, but to genuinely get to know them. 
When it was time to meet the various teams here, social media, video, creative, they offered to collaborate, share ideas and be a voice. 
Throughout the day, I kept on hearing... tell me more... and what can we do? They wanted to talk to everyone! 
We ended the night by going to the Hostage Square, filled with visual sentimental displays, families & friends holding signs of hostages, reporters, musical circles, and hundreds of people showing up to support the cause to #bringthemhomenow
Brett and Ari are staunch Israel supporters and have been non-stop helping. I felt like I made 2 new friends as well! Thank you for coming!

Remember that rockstar moment when Representative Ayanna Pressley compared the Israeli army to "violent white supremacists." - Not the Chinese Army, which rounds up Uyghur Muslims in the dark of night and takes them to slave-labor "re-education" camps. Not the Iranian security police, who literally hang homosexuals. Not the Pakistani army, which regularly beats and oppresses the Baloch people. No other countries were referenced by Pressley as a parallel to the horror and stain of Jim Crow racism – only the one Jewish state was shoehorned into that mendacious comparison. Tlaib claimed the Israeli response to Hamas firing rockets on Israel is connected to the struggles of black people in the United States! It’s super hard to pick my favorite though.. cause no one in Congress works harder to drum up J3w-baiting at home and abroad than AOC. You may recognize Avinatan Or from a video released by Hamas terrorists wherein his girlfriend Noa was being driven away from him on an all-terrain vehicle pleading for her life, arms reaching for Avinatan who is being marched away by terrorists. 

To Avinatan:
I close my eyes and imagine you, wherever it is that you are. I hold my breath because it’s hard to breathe knowing what you’re enduring. I hold my breath and hope for a moment you’re not cold, you’re not afraid, and you don’t feel alone. I hope you can feel us weeping for your suffering and pleading for your return. I wish you could see all of us around the world wearing a necklace as a symbol of our commitment to your safe return. I hope one day you are able to read this from your sofa with Noa beside you.  I hope this nightmare will one day be a distant memory muffled by beautiful ones, like your child’s first word-I hope it’s “אבא.” I hope next year on the last night of Hanukkah, you will be lighting your own menorah so I don’t have to light one on your behalf, like I will tonight.

We had the privilege of speaking with Aaron who was injured by Hamas at @sheba.medical.center . Listen to his story. It is the story of many.

We visited @magen_david_adom  headquarters in Jerusalem and listened to your last words. You dialed the emergency line and asked the dispatcher to be connected to your father. The dispatcher dials and your father answers. 

“Dad, I love you.” 
“Where are you? What’s wrong?”
“I love you” you repeat.  You speak in a whisper as they close in on you. Your father interrupts as he begins to understand what you mean as you repeat it again, “I love you, Dad.” He responds in a panic “Son, what do you see in front of you?” Your father hears the gunshots. You say it once more-“Dad, I love you” this time, he replies- “I love you too, son.” 

They tried to fill your last moments with terror. You filled them with love.

Omer, come home. We’re waiting for you. Your room is in the exact condition you left it. Clothing strewn about, bed unmade. A mess.. Your mother won’t let anyone touch a thing. It is you, she insists, who will clean it. She enters every morning to tell you the days’ agenda and she returns every night for a recap. No one will sit in your seat or sleep in your bed or play your guitar or use your computer. Your inhaler still has medicine left in the canister and it is you who will use every last drop before it expires. On your first Shabbat dinner back, your dad will pass you the wine first, even though you’re the baby of the family. You’ll tell a story and make your brother and sister laugh, the way you always do. You’ll get up and dance with your two left feet, my god how you love to dance. Your mom will hug you tight and kiss you on the forehead and never again have to say, “Omer, come home. We’re waiting for you.”

In 1877, Jewish poet Naftali Herz Imber wrote “Hatikvah,” The Hope. It reflects the 2,000-year-old desire of the Jewish people to return to our indigenous land where we could live in the freedom and safety we had not been granted in the diaspora for thousands of years. On October 7th, in kibbutz Kfar Aza, our people were brutally massacred in their homes. They were murdered for being Jewish. Today we stand here, on these tragedy soaked grounds, in their memory and in their honor. We stand tall with love in our hearts, an act of defiance against those who have tried to erase us throughout history. We sing loud so the world will hear, we’re not going anywhere. “Our hope is not yet lost, the hope of two thousand years, to be a free nation in our own land, the land of Zion and Jerusalem.” 
עם ישראל חי
